# error classes in reducers are auto-imported by name reference

In reducer code, you reference error classes by name without importing them:

```typescript
// ✅ Just reference the error — auto-imported
throw new MissingIdError("ID is required");
throw new EntryNotFoundError("Entry not found");

// ❌ Don't manually import
import { MissingIdError } from "../../gen/module-name/error.js";
throw new MissingIdError("ID is required");

// ❌ Don't use nested access patterns
throw new errors.ModuleName.MissingIdError("message");
```

The code generator scans reducer code for error class references and adds the appropriate imports automatically. Manually importing creates duplicate imports or path mismatches.

Since [[error names must end with Error and use PascalCase]], the generator matches on the PascalCase class name ending in "Error".

